5 to 1119","1119":"1119","Dyffryn Clwyd, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales","Dyffryn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom":"Dyffryn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Efa","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of several Anglicized forms of the Gaelic name Eithne . In the case of Queen Victoria's granddaughter Princess Ena (Victoria Eugénie Julia Ena,  1887–1969 ) it had a different origin: it was a misreading by the minister who baptized her off a handwritten note of the originally intended name   Eva .  In England, the name is remembered principally as that of the fearsome  Ena Sharples  in the television soap opera Coronation Street.  See also  Ina ."],"variants":[{"name":"Eithne","meanings":["Traditional name, apparently from <i>eithne</i> ‘kernel’, which was used as a term of praise in bardic poetry. St Eithne was a daughter of King Laoghaire and one of St Patrick's first converts."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Efa ferch Llywelyn was born about 1024, in Denbighshire, Wales, her father, Llywelyn ap Dolphyn, was 31 and her mother, Tangwystl ferch Iorwerth, was 24. She married Einudd ap Morien about 1054, in Dyffryn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died from 1065 to 1119, in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1024–from 1065 to 1119":"umbes 1024–1065 kuni 1119","1024–1119":"1024–1119","1030–1065":"1030–1065","1020–1094":"1020–1094","1055–1134":"1055–1134","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1063–1132":"1063–1132","0995–Male":"0995–Surnud","1002–Female":"1002–Surnud","about 1060":"umbes 1060","about 1063":"umbes 1063","1055":"1055","1132":"1132","1065":"1065","1020":"1020","1063":"1063","1030":"1030","1094":"1094","1060":"1060","0995":"0995","1002":"1002","1134":"1134","1024":"1024","about 1024":"umbes 1024","about 1054":"umbes 1054","from 1065 to 1119":"1065 kuni 1119","1119":"1119","Dyffryn Clwyd, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales","Dyffryn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom":"Dyffryn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1024–from 1065 to 1119":"noin 1024–vuodesta 1065 vuoteen 1119","1024–1119":"1024–1119","1030–1065":"1030–1065","1020–1094":"1020–1094","1055–1134":"1055–1134","1060–Male":"1060–Kuollut","1063–1132":"1063–1132","0995–Male":"0995–Kuollut","1002–Female":"1002–Kuollut","about 1060":"noin 1060","about 1063":"noin 1063","1055":"1055","1132":"1132","1065":"1065","1020":"1020","1063":"1063","1030":"1030","1094":"1094","1060":"1060","0995":"0995","1002":"1002","1134":"1134","1024":"1024","about 1024":"noin 1024","about 1054":"noin 1054","from 1065 to 1119":"vuodesta 1065 vuoteen 1119","1119":"1119","Dyffryn Clwyd,